@database psnup.guide

@width 72

@node main "psnup.guide"

PSUtils Release 1 Patchlevel 16


NAME
psnup - multiple pages per sheet


SYNOPSIS

@{b}psnup@{ub} [@{b}-w@{ub}@{i}width@{ui}] [@{b}-h@{ub}@{i}height@{ui}] [@{b}-p@{ub}@{i}paper@{ui}] [@{b}-W@{ub}@{i}width@{ui}] [@{b}-H@{ub}@{i}height@{ui}] [@{b}-P@{ub}@{i}paper@{ui}]
      [@{b}-l@{ub}][@{b}-r@{ub}] [@{b}-f@{ub}] [@{b}-c@{ub}]
      [@{b}-m@{ub}@{i}margin@{ui}] [@{b}-b@{ub}@{i}border@{ui}] [@{b}-d@{ub}@{i}lwidth@{ui}] [@{b}-s@{ub}@{i}scale@{ui}] [@{b}-@{ub}@{i}nup@{ui}]
      [@{b}-q@{ub}] @{i}infile@{ui} @{i}outfile@{ui}


@{i}`Online help' : @{b}psnup -? @{ub}@{ui}


DESCRIPTION

@{i}Psnup@{ui} puts multiple logical pages onto each physical sheet of paper.
The input PostScript file should follow the Adobe Document Structuring
Conventions.

The @{b}-w@{ub} option gives the paper width, and the @{b}-h@{ub} option gives the paper
height, normally specified in @{b}"cm"@{ub} or @{b}"in"@{ub} to convert PostScript's
points (1/72 of an inch) to centimeters or inches.

The @{b}-p@{ub} option can be used as an alternative, to set the paper size to
@{b}a3, a4, a5, b5, letter, legal, tabloid, statement, executive, folio,
quarto@{ub} or @{b}10x14@{ub}.

The default paper size is @{b}a4@{ub} @{i}(If you re-compile the program, you
have the opportunity to #def PAPER - DF).@{ui}

The @{b}-W@{ub}, @{b}-H@{ub}, and @{b}-P@{ub} options set the input paper size, if it is
different from the output size. This makes it easy to impose
pages of one size on a different size of paper.

The @{b}-l@{ub} option should be used for pages which are in landscape
orientation (rotated 90 degrees anticlockwise). The @{b}-r@{ub} option
should be used for pages which are in seascape orientation (rotated 90
degrees clockwise), and the @{b}-f@{ub} option should be used for pages
which have the width and height interchanged, but are not rotated.


@{i}Psnup@{ui} normally uses `row-major' layout, where adjacent pages are
placed in rows across the paper.  The @{b}-c@{ub} option changes the order
to `column-major', where successive pages are placed in columns down
the paper.

A margin to leave around the whole page can be specified with the
@{b}-m@{ub} option. This is useful for sheets of `thumbnail' pages,
because the normal page margins are reduced by putting multiple pages
on a single sheet.

@{i}This is particularly the case if your printer cannot print to the very
edge of the paper.  For example, my bj200ex cannot print within the top
four millimetres of the page.  It has an even larger `non-printable width'
on the other sides, but the top side is the most important because most
documents do not print so closely to the other sides. - DF@{ui}

The @{b}-b@{ub} option is used to specify an additional margin around each page
on a sheet.

The @{b}-d@{ub} option draws a line around the border of each page, of the
specified width. If the @{i}width@{ui} parameter is omitted, a default linewidth
of 1 point is assumed. The linewidth is relative to the original
page dimensions, @{i}i.e.@{ui} it is scaled down with the rest of the page.

The scale chosen by @{i}psnup@{ui} can be overridden with the @{b}-s@{ub} option.
This is useful to merge pages which are already reduced.

The @{b}-@{ub}@{i}nup@{ui} option selects the number of logical pages to put on each
sheet of paper. This can be any whole number; @{i}psnup@{ui} tries to
optimise the layout so that the minimum amount of space is wasted. If
@{i}psnup@{ui} cannot find a layout within its tolerance limit, it will
abort with an error message.  The alternative form @{b}-n @{ub}@{i}nup@{ui} can also
be used, for compatibility with other n-up programs.

@{i}Psnup@{ui} normally prints the page numbers of the pages re-arranged;
the @{b}-q@{ub} option suppresses this.


EXAMPLES

The potential use of this utility is varied but one particular 
use is in conjunction with @{i}psbook(1)@{ui}.

For example, using groff to create a PostScript document and lpr as 
the @{i}UNIX @{ui}print spooler a typical command line might look like this:

groff -Tps -ms @{i}file@{ui} | psbook | psnup -2 | lpr

Where file is a 4 page document this command will result in a 
two page document printing two pages of @{i}file@{ui} per page and
rearranges the page order to match the input pages 4 and 1 
on the first output page and
pages 2 then 3 of the input document 
on the second output page.


